ermining who shall be labeled as retarded. Second, she recommends that the clinicians use the two-dimensional definition of retardation proposed by the American Association of Mental Deficiency, subnormality in both intellectual performance and adaptive behavior. Third, she concludes that pluralistic assessment procedures must be employed to take into account cultural biases in IQ tests designed to measure cognitive skills. This title is part of UC Press's Voices Revived program, which commemorates University of California Press's mission to seek out and cultivate the brightest minds and give them voice, reach, and impact. Drawing on a backlist dating to 1893, Voices Revived makes high-quality, peer-reviewed scholarship accessible once again using print-on-demand technology. This title was originally published in 1973.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aIntellectual disability. 0aIntelligence tests. 0aPeople with mental disabilitieszCaliforniazRiverside. 0aPsychological tests. 0aSchools. 0aSocial history. 4aintelligence. 4amedical sociology. 4amedicine. 4apsychology. 4areasoning. 4asocial aspects. 4asociology. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520311503?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520311503423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520311503/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles